Yes, EMD is a real company that really produced a locomotive called the FT
well, yes and no
it was 2 independant parts, an "A" unit (with a cab) and a "b" unit without a cab
at the outset, railroads purchased diesels on a 1:1 replacement basis for steam
so they would purchase a certain number of units, with a cab each end to replace 1 steam train
usually these consists were A-B-A or A-B-B-A
this is of course because american trains were (still are) much longer and heavvier than european
Eventually, railroads learned that diesel locomotives were more flexible than steam and started to just put as many locos as needed for any given route
so they were usually not permanently coupled to anything at all
did you enjoy your rail history for the day? :)

column8: German Festival Trains Transport - patched version
column9: certainly  ;)
American diesels almost always have one cab while european ones generally have two, this is because most american diesels still run in pairs
